{"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Enrolment","identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.yeomessaging.YEOFR\/documentation\/YEOFR\/EnrollmentProgress","doc:\/\/com.yeomessaging.YEOFR\/documentation\/YEOFR\/LightingPhaseConfig"],"generated":true,"anchor":"Enrolment"}],"primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"tokens":[{"text":"enum","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PoseTarget","kind":"identifier"}],"languages":["swift"],"platforms":["iOS","iPadOS","Mac Catalyst"]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"content":[{"anchor":"overview","text":"Overview","type":"heading","level":2},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Used by the Luxand gallery walk to gate per-pose capture on the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"user’s actual head orientation (Vision’s "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"VNFaceObservation.yaw"},{"type":"text","text":" \/"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":".pitch"},{"type":"text","text":"). Without this gate the SDK would auto-advance within ~50 ms"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of pose acceptance — the user has no time to physically change"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"orientation, so every captured appearance reflects the same head"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"pose and the gallery gains no angular breadth."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Thresholds were picked to match the user’s normal head-turn range"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"during walking: a low ±7° on the yaw turn poses (Vision compresses"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"physical head rotation, so a larger gate forces an exaggerated turn —"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"see "},{"code":"yawThreshold","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"), and a tight ±5° on "},{"code":".front","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" so it only matches"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"when the user is genuinely centred while still leaving a 2° dead-band"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"below the yaw gate. Vision reports yaw\/pitch in radians (≈ 0.26 rad"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"per 15°)."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Vision sign conventions"}]},{"type":"text","text":" on the rotated, mirrored front-camera"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"portrait buffer ("},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"VNFaceObservation"},{"type":"text","text":" reads geometry from the buffer"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"as-presented to Vision — the selfie mirror flips the apparent"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"rotation):"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"text":"yaw","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":": POSITIVE = head turned to the user’s LEFT (subject’s"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"POV), NEGATIVE = head turned to the user’s RIGHT. This is the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"opposite of the world-frame “right turn = positive” convention"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"because the front-camera buffer is mirror-imaged before Vision"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"sees it.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"pitch"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":": positive = chin DOWN (face tilts towards the bottom","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of the rotated buffer), negative = chin UP. This is the opposite","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of the colloquial “looking up = positive” convention."}]}]}]}],"kind":"content"}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/